INSERT INTO program_sops (module_id, sop_number, title, content, quality_bars, deliverables, tools_used, dependencies, version)
VALUES (
  'm0',
  '0-104',
  'Google Ads & Agency Service Positioning — Selling High-Ticket Ad Management Through Intro Offers and Full-Funnel Ownership',
  $body$## Overview
Google Ads management is a commodity service — competing on "we do it better" requires perfect timing and unhappy clients. Break out by repositioning around full-funnel ownership, using a low-friction intro offer to sell to the entire market, and targeting high-CPC verticals where funnel optimization ROI is obvious.

## Steps

### Phase 1: Reframe What You Sell

1. **Audit your scope** — If your deliverables begin and end inside the Google Ads account, you are in the commodity zone.
2. **Expand to full-funnel ownership** — Control landing pages, conversion copy, video assets, and the post-click experience. In high-CPC verticals ($250+/click), optimizing ads without owning the funnel is optimizing a leaky bucket.
3. **Reposition your statement** — Stop saying "Google Ads manager." Describe the outcome: conversion rate improvement, CPA reduction, or full-funnel customer acquisition.

### Phase 2: Design a Low-Friction Intro Offer

4. **Create a one-time fixed-price offer (~$2,500)** — It layers on top of what the prospect already does. Must NOT require firing their current agency or making a long-term commitment.

:::tip From the Field
Deliver the intro offer for ~$500 so margins hold even when guarantees pay out (expect ~1 in 10 to trigger). Use the 2-week delivery window as a client filter: assess fit, results, and whether they can afford $10K/month — then close roughly 1 in 10 intro clients onto the backend. This makes your entire acquisition funnel cash-flow positive and scalable on paid channels.
:::

5. **Attach a performance guarantee** — Example: "We build a landing page that beats your existing conversion rate — or it's free." This specific offer scaled a CRO agency to $900k/month within 12 months.
6. **Map the backend upsell** — Intro ($2,500 one-time): custom landing page + conversion test. Backend ($5,000-$12,000/month): ongoing CRO, landing page iteration, full-funnel ads management.
7. **Script the transition** — "We proved we can beat your conversion rate. Here's what ongoing engagement looks like."

### Phase 3: Target the Right Clients

8. **Prioritize high-CPC verticals** — Legal, medical, financial services, home services ($100-$500+/click). A 20% conversion rate improvement on $250 clicks saves tens of thousands/month.
9. **Target legacy brands over Meta-native D2C** — Brands that grew on cheap Meta CPMs often resist Google. Legacy brands already understand paid search and value it as a core acquisition lever.
10. **Disqualify bad fits early** — Avoid clients who view Google Ads as background support, refuse to invest in landing pages, or comparison-shop purely on management fee.

### Phase 4: Operationalize and Scale

11. **Productize the intro offer** — Template the landing pages, standardize A/B testing methodology, fix a 3-week delivery timeline.
12. **Track intro-to-backend conversion rate** — Below 30% means your intro delivery quality or upsell path needs work.
13. **Build a case study library** — Document before/after conversion rates, CPL improvements, and revenue impact from every intro engagement.

## Key Lessons

- Sell the funnel/outcome, not account management — competing on "better Google Ads" is a race to the bottom.
- At $250/click, the biggest lever is almost always post-click; optimizing bids while sending traffic to a bad landing page is malpractice.
- A one-time, risk-reversed intro offer removes every objection (timing, switching costs, trust) and lets you sell to the whole market.
- The $900k/month CRO case study proves the model: $2,500 intro offer with "beat your conversion rate or free" guarantee, $5-12k/month backend.
- Legacy brands that predate Meta arbitrage are better-fit clients than D2C brands that grew on cheap Meta CPMs.

## Common Mistakes

- Staying inside the ads account and not building landing pages, copy, or creative — leaves the biggest performance levers untouched and makes you replaceable.
- Trying to sell $5-10k/month retainers to cold prospects without an intro offer to bridge the trust gap.
- Running a $2,500 intro offer without a clear upsell path into recurring revenue — that's a project-based agency, not a business.
- Targeting Meta-native D2C brands who will underinvest, deprioritize your work, and attribute all growth to Meta.
- Competing on management fee or percentage of ad spend instead of outcomes and guarantees.$body$,
  '[{"check":"Intro offer must include performance guarantee (e.g., ''beat conversion rate or free'') to remove objections and enable market-wide selling","severity":"critical"},{"check":"Intro-to-backend conversion rate must be 30%+ or quality/upsell path needs revision","severity":"critical"},{"check":"Full-funnel ownership must be part of positioning (landing pages, conversion copy, post-click experience) — not isolated Google Ads account management","severity":"critical"},{"check":"Avoid staying inside ads account only; leaving biggest performance levers untouched makes agency replaceable","severity":"warning"},{"check":"Target high-CPC verticals ($100-500+/click) and legacy brands, not Meta-native D2C brands prone to underinvestment and channel attribution disputes","severity":"warning"},{"check":"Deliver intro offer for ~$500 cost to ensure margins hold when guarantees trigger (~1 in 10 rate)","severity":"info"}]'::jsonb,
  '[{"type":"operating_playbook","description":"Google Ads agency positioning playbook covering reframing from commodity account management to full-funnel ownership, designing intro offers with performance guarantees, targeting ideal client verticals, and operationalizing upsell paths"},{"type":"outreach_campaign","description":"Client targeting strategy for high-CPC verticals (legal, medical, financial, home services) and legacy brands, with positioning around conversion rate improvement and CPA reduction outcomes"}]'::jsonb,
  ARRAY[]::text[],
  ARRAY[]::text[],
  1
)
