INSERT INTO program_sops (module_id, sop_number, title, content, quality_bars, deliverables, tools_used, dependencies, version)
VALUES (
  'm6',
  '6-4',
  'Full-Funnel Orchestration — The Holy Trinity',
  $body$## The Big Picture

The LinkedIn GTM system is not any single channel. It's the **orchestration** of all channels hitting the same audience from different angles. When someone sees your content, your DMs, your ads, and your emails — they think "this person is everywhere." That's the goal.

## The Holy Trinity: Content + DMs + Ads

| Channel | Purpose | Tool |
|---------|---------|------|
| **Organic Content** | Build authority, generate engagement | LinkedIn + LeadShark |
| **Direct Messages** | Start 1:1 conversations | HeyReach |
| **LinkedIn Ads** | Guarantee ICP sees your content | Campaign Manager (Thought Leadership Ads) |

Each channel reinforces the others. Ads drive more profile views → you reach out to profile viewers. DMs start conversations → they see your ads and content. Content builds trust → DMs convert better.

## Recommended Build Order

Don't try to launch everything at once. Build one channel per week:

1. **Week 1: Lead magnets + LeadShark** — Create a lead magnet, post it, set up LeadShark to auto-deliver via DM. This validates your offer.
2. **Week 2: DM campaign** — Use HeyReach to send your validated lead magnet to existing connections who match your ICP.
3. **Week 3: LinkedIn Ads** — Take your best-performing organic lead magnet post, set up a Thought Leadership Ad campaign targeting your matched audience.
4. **Week 4: Cold email** (optional) — Layer in cold email using Clay + your email platform for people you can't reach on LinkedIn.

## The Compounding Effect

Top of funnel activity compounds over time. Each lead magnet you create, each post you boost, each DM campaign you run — they all build on each other. Someone who saw your ad in January might reply to your DM in March and book a call in May.

This is why consistency matters more than perfection. Make a new lead magnet every week. Post it. See what works. Boost the winners. Keep DMing your list. The numbers will come.

## When to Add Cold Email

Cold email is not required for everyone. Ask yourself:

- **Do I already have a list?** If yes, DMs and ads may be enough to start.
- **How much experimentation am I planning?** If a lot, Clay is amazing for flexible workflow building.
- **Do I need one specific workflow?** If yes, you can operationalize it outside of Clay — you don't need an infinity-workflow tool for one workflow.

Start with DMs + Ads. Get leads flowing. Then layer in cold email when you're ready for more volume.

:::tip From the Field
Automated LinkedIn connection requests are the highest-ROI first step — low setup cost, ongoing lead gen benefit. Prioritize these before cold email infrastructure (domain purchasing, warming). When you do add cold email via Clay, hyper-personalize at scale by referencing a prospect's recent LinkedIn post and their specific engagement metrics in the opening line — this makes bulk outreach feel individually written and dramatically increases response rates.
:::

:::warning Common Question
"Why not just pick one channel and master it?" No single channel is a silver bullet, and every channel gets noisier over time. Different buyers prefer different channels — some never check LinkedIn DMs, some ignore email. Multi-channel increases your probability of reaching someone when they're in-market. Even a small slice done well compounds.
:::

## Tool Stack Summary

| Tool | Role |
|------|------|
| **LeadShark** | Auto-deliver lead magnets via DM when someone comments on a post |
| **HeyReach** | Automated connection requests and DM campaigns |
| **LinkedIn Campaign Manager** | Run Thought Leadership Ads to matched audiences |
| **Magnet Lab** | Create lead magnets, host landing pages, run email sequences |
| **Clay** | Flexible data enrichment and list building (primarily for cold email) |

:::tip From the Field
Clay has fundamentally shifted the game from technical execution to creative strategy. The technical side — uploading CSVs, jerry-rigging integrations — is now trivially easy. Differentiation today comes from creativity: how interesting your campaigns are, how relevant your AI-generated copy feels, finding unique lead sources, and writing highly personalized emails that don't feel automated.
:::

## The Mindset

> "The average B2B business owner is kind of shuttling around through the Internet like a pinball in a pinball machine. They have a 10-second memory and they do what kind of hits them last. You really need to hit them a lot from different sides." — Tim Keen

Don't overthink. Don't try to find the perfect message. Build the machine, keep it running, and iterate based on what the market tells you.

:::tip From the Field
Specific workflows and tools in this space become obsolete almost immediately — sometimes before you've finished learning them. Invest in understanding the *underlying principles* (why a tactic works, what signal it exploits) so you can rebuild your own processes as the landscape shifts. Mental models are durable; specific processes are perishable.
:::

:::tip From the Field
Lead generation is inherently messy — embrace it. There's no "one and done" magic solution. The process involves wrangling different data points, thinking on your feet, and adapting in real time. This messiness is actually valuable: running it manually first teaches you more about your ideal clients and how they exist on the internet than any automated solution would. Treat it like an analytical, process-based system with four integrated channels (lead magnets, prospect lists, cold email/DMs, and LinkedIn ads targeting specific individuals by name). If even a quarter of those channels work, you'll get results. For your first campaign, manually write one perfect email to understand what converts — don't automate until the manual version is proven.
:::$body$,
  '[{"check":"Multi-channel execution: All three channels (organic content, DMs, LinkedIn ads) are deployed within 4 weeks, not isolated tactics","severity":"critical"},{"check":"Lead magnet validation before scaling: Lead magnet must be tested via LeadShark on organic post before spending ad budget or cold email volume","severity":"critical"},{"check":"Manual execution first: Before automating any workflow, prove conversion with manually written, personalized outreach","severity":"warning"},{"check":"Consistency over perfection: New lead magnets generated weekly and deployed across channels, not one-time campaigns","severity":"warning"},{"check":"Hyper-personalization in cold email: Cold outreach references specific LinkedIn activity or recent posts, not generic templates","severity":"info"}]'::jsonb,
