INSERT INTO program_sops (module_id, sop_number, title, content, quality_bars, deliverables, tools_used, dependencies, version)
VALUES (
  'm6',
  '6-106',
  'Agency Acquisition & AI Automation Playbook',
  $body$## Overview
Target $2-5M single-service agencies with ~20% margins and tired owners. Deploy AI automation to double capacity without adding headcount, pushing profit from ~$600K to $1-2M EBITDA -- crossing the threshold that attracts serious M&A buyers.

## Steps

1. **Define your ideal target** -- Single-service agencies in non-digitally native industries (e.g., SEO for addiction treatment, LinkedIn for professional services) with $2-5M revenue, ~20% margins, and an operationally fatigued owner.
2. **Qualify on profit, not revenue** -- A $3M agency at 20% margins produces $600K profit, below the $1M EBITDA floor for serious buyers. The gap between current profit and that floor is your value creation thesis.
3. **Identify owner motivation** -- Look for owners who want to sell but can't command a meaningful multiple. They typically think "I need more sales" when the real answer is "I need more profit per client."
4. **Run an AI automation audit** -- Map every repeatable manual task: reporting, split test setup/analysis, platform data extraction, insights generation, report assembly, copy/creative iteration.
5. **Deploy AI to double capacity on existing headcount** -- Automate the tasks above. If a $2.5M agency had $1M profit, doubling capacity without proportional cost increases pushes profit toward $2M.
6. **Maintain speed-of-learning as your moat** -- The field only started scaling in late 2024. Build a habit of weekly tool evaluation and workflow iteration. The moment you slow down, the advantage erodes.
7. **Position for exit or roll-up** -- Once EBITDA crosses $1-2M, the agency qualifies for strategic buyers, roll-ups, or can be held at improved margins.

:::tip From the Field
Take 50-51% equity when parachuting into agencies — add $5-10M in enterprise value over 6-12 months of operational improvements, then sell to PE-backed buyers for a $2.5-5M exit. The original owner can stay for a second wave or exit completely.
:::

## Key Lessons
- Profit determines exit viability -- $1M+ EBITDA is the hard floor for serious M&A buyers.
- Single-service niche agencies have the strongest margins, most defensible positioning, and are often undervalued by their owners.
- Automating reporting, data pulls, analysis, and copy generation can double capacity on the same cost base without growing revenue.
- Tired owners misdiagnose their problem as "need more clients" when it's "need more profit per client" -- this is your acquisition leverage.
- Speed of learning is the only durable moat in AI consulting.

:::tip From the Field
Building your agency on a proprietary software stack (using AI coding tools like Claude Code to programmatically build against APIs for onboarding, domain config, email warmup) creates deeper defensibility than speed-of-learning alone — legacy SaaS vendors with years of tech debt can't replicate it quickly.
:::

## Common Mistakes
- Targeting based on revenue alone -- a $5M agency at 10% margins ($500K) is worse than a $2.5M agency at 30% ($750K).
- Assuming the owner will accept a fair price -- educate on profit-based multiples early to reset revenue-based valuations.
- Trying to automate everything at once -- start with highest-volume, lowest-complexity tasks (reporting, data extraction) for fastest ROI.
- Hiring instead of automating -- every new hire adds cost, overhead, and margin compression.
- Ignoring the niche -- generalist agencies are harder to operate, position, and sell than specialists at the same revenue.
- Underestimating tool churn -- what worked in Q1 may be obsolete by Q3. Allocate dedicated time for evaluation.$body$,
  '[{"check":"Target agency must have $2-5M revenue with minimum 20% EBITDA margins to justify acquisition","severity":"critical"},{"check":"Post-automation profit must reach $1M+ EBITDA to attract serious M&A buyers","severity":"critical"},{"check":"AI automation should double capacity without proportional headcount or cost increases","severity":"critical"},{"check":"Avoid targeting revenue-only; always validate profit margins before acquisition","severity":"warning"},{"check":"Maintain weekly tool evaluation and workflow iteration to sustain competitive moat","severity":"warning"},{"check":"Automate high-volume, low-complexity tasks first (reporting, data extraction) before attempting comprehensive automation","severity":"info"}]'::jsonb,
  '[{"type":"operating_playbook","description":"Step-by-step playbook for identifying, acquiring, automating, and exiting single-service agencies"},{"type":"diagnostic_report","description":"AI automation audit identifying repeatable manual tasks for capacity doubling"}]'::jsonb,
  ARRAY[]::text[],
  ARRAY[]::text[],
  1
)
